          <avActivityHighlights>Gradual increase in danger of dry avalanches as a consequence of new snow and strong wind.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>As a consequence of new snow and strong wind the prevalence and size of the avalanche prone locations will increase. Even emptied starting zones will be replenished as a consequence of snowfall and wind, in particular along the border with France and along the border with Switzerland. &lt;br/&gt; Especially on very steep slopes and on wind-loaded slopes medium-sized and, in isolated cases, large natural avalanches are to be expected. Here the avalanches can be triggered in deep layers of the snowpack and reach very large size. &lt;br/&gt; Single winter sport participants can release avalanches. Caution is to be exercised on steep slopes, and in gullies and bowls, and behind abrupt changes in the terrain. &lt;br/&gt; The conditions are precarious for backcountry touring and other off-piste activities outside marked and open pistes.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>Over a wide area 30 to 40 cm of snow, and up to 80 cm in some localities, will fall until Monday above approximately 1600 m. The wind will be strong. &lt;br/&gt; The fresh snow as well as the wind slabs that are forming during the snowfall will become increasingly prone to triggering. &lt;br/&gt; The snowpack is unfavourably layered. &lt;br/&gt; Adjacent to ridgelines and in pass areas snow depths vary greatly, depending on the infuence of the wind. &lt;br/&gt; Several slab avalanches have been released in the last few days.</snowpackStructureComment>
          <tendencyComment>The weather conditions will facilitate a slow strengthening of the snowpack.</tendencyComment>
